\pard\b\fs30 1 Concept and architecture\b0\fs22\par
\pard\b\fs26 1.1 Purpose and authority\b0\fs22\par
\pard\sa220 THOG2 is a compact transformer-weight architecture. Its purpose is to explore whether repeated transformer-block weights can be represented by a much smaller learned coefficient structure without destroying useful model capacity. This document is authoritative for compact non-dense geometry names, semantic decomposition, coefficient shapes, compact-order meanings, aliases, basis-shim obligations, and reporting obligations.\par
\pard\sa220 Dense remains the conventional GPT control path. Dense is not a compact geometry and shall not be forced through compact basis identity. The dense path must stay clean and useful as an equal-wall and equal-memory control.\par
\pard\sa220 This revision integrates the original Chebyshev-native GPT-2 discussion only where it clarifies boundaries. The current sheet work remains a THOG2 compact-weight geometry pass, not a Chebyshev-native residual-stream model.\par
\pard\b\fs26 1.2 Architectural concept\b0\fs22\par
\pard\sa220 A transformer block contains repeated matrix families: QKV input projection, attention output projection, MLP expansion, and MLP contraction. In an ordinary dense GPT, every layer owns dense matrix parameters for these families. In THOG2, a non-dense geometry stores learned coefficient tensors and deterministic orthogonal bases. At execution time, these coefficients and bases generate the layer-specific dense-equivalent matrix, or an equivalent direct factorised computation.\par
\pard\sa220 The important distinction is between persistent trained state and ephemeral computation. The dense-equivalent matrix may be materialised locally for a kernel, but optimizer state, gradients, and learned model degrees of freedom live in the compact coefficient representation. This is why a geometry can be valuable even when it materialises a dense-equivalent matrix during the forward path.\par
\pard\b\fs26 1.3 Residual-stream interface\b0\fs22\par
\pard\sa220 Token IDs are mapped through learned token embeddings. Positions are represented by the ordinary positional embedding mechanism unless a later specification explicitly changes that. There is no special Chebyshev input sequence interface in this requirements version. Compact weight geometry applies to repeated weight families across depth and selected matrix axes, not to vocabulary index space.\par
\pard\b\fs26 1.4 Depth, sheets, and blocks\b0\fs22\par
\pard\sa220 Depth is the privileged compact axis. It corresponds to repeated transformer layers. A depth-only geometry learns a depth trajectory for each scalar matrix element. A sheet geometry learns a surface over depth and one matrix axis. A block geometry learns a field over depth and both matrix axes.\par
\pard\sa220 These are different experiments. A depth geometry preserves both matrix axes whole. A generic sheet compresses a flattened input or output axis. A semantic sheet chooses the second compressed axis according to transformer semantics. A block compresses both axes and therefore changes more than a sheet. Names shall not hide these distinctions.\par
\pard\b\fs26 1.5 Clean-axis rule\b0\fs22\par
\pard\sa220 Every compact geometry shall state exactly which axes are compressed and which axes remain whole. Generic geometries may flatten axes because their purpose is to test generic compression. Semantic geometries shall not flatten across axes that the design declares semantically distinct.\par
\pard\sa220 QKV role, attention head, local head channel, residual d_model channel, and MLP hidden channel are distinct semantic axes. A semantic sheet preset shall not introduce basis sharing across QKV role or attention head. A semantic MLP sheet preset shall not introduce basis sharing across hidden_channel. Any future exception must be introduced under a new explicit geometry name.\par
\pard\b\fs26 1.6 Integrated catalogue principle\b0\fs22\par
\pard\sa220 All non-dense geometries shall be resolved through one integrated catalogue. The catalogue shall decompose each compact preset into an MLP component, a QKV component, and an attention-output component. The old two-slot model, preset to attention_geometry plus mlp_geometry, is no longer expressive enough because QKV and attention output require independent choices.\par
\pard\sa220 Existing geometries are not debris. generic_sheet_col, depth, mlp_block, head_aware_block, and full_block remain first-class entries. New semantic sheet components are added to the same system rather than bolted on as special cases.\par
\page
\pard\b\fs30 2 Definitions and notation\b0\fs22\par
\pard\b\fs26 2.1 Dimension symbols\b0\fs22\par
\pard\f1\fs19\sa120 L = number of transformer layers.\tab D = residual model width, n_embd.\tab H = number of attention heads.\par
\pard\f1\fs19\sa120 Dh = per-head channel width, D / H.\tab M = MLP hidden width, usually 4D.\par
\pard\f1\fs19\sa120 P = depth order.\tab Q = attention/residual d_model order.\tab J = QKV local per-head channel order.\par
\pard\f1\fs19\sa120 O = attention-output local per-head channel order.\tab X = MLP d_model order.\tab Y = MLP hidden order.\par
\pard\f1\fs19\sa120 q_in = resolved generic input-axis order.\tab q_out = resolved generic output-axis order.\par
\pard\b\fs26 2.2 Repeated matrix families\b0\fs22\par
\pard\sa180 The repeated matrix families are attention_input_weight, attention_output_weight, mlp_expansion_weight, and mlp_contraction_weight. The packed QKV projection may also be viewed semantically as W_qkv[qkv_role, head, local_head_channel, d_model_input]. The attention output may be viewed as W_out[d_model_output, head, local_head_channel].\par
\pard\sa180 LayerNorm vectors, biases, embeddings, and unembedding may have compact handling where already supported, but the normative geometry catalogue in this document is concerned with the four repeated matrix families above.\par
\pard\b\fs26 2.3 Basis families and compact orders\b0\fs22\par
\pard\sa220 Chebyshev is the primary compact basis family. DCT is also a supported or planned orthogonal basis family under the same geometry contract. The basis family and basis version shall be recorded in compact identity. A coefficient tensor shall never be silently interpreted under a different basis family or basis version.\par
\pard\sa220 In this sheet-geometry pass, a basis family is a deterministic weight-coordinate generator. It is not required to provide polynomial product tensors, activation order-growth rules, projection rules, or function-space nonlinearities. Those belong to a later Chebyshev-native residual-stream model, not this THOG2 compact-weight pass.\par
\pard\b\fs26 2.4 Minimal basis-registry shim\b0\fs22\par
\pard\sa160 2.4.1 Before adding new semantic sheet geometries, the implementation shall introduce a narrow basis registry that centralises accepted basis names, artifact tags, basis versions, and basis-matrix construction.\par
\pard\sa160 2.4.2 The shim shall support the existing Chebyshev and DCT families without changing their numerical behaviour.\par
\pard\sa160 2.4.3 The shim shall expose only the capabilities needed by current THOG2 compact-weight geometry: name, artifact_tag, version, basis_matrix, and supports_native_products metadata.\par
\pard\sa160 2.4.4 The shim shall not introduce product_tensor, metric, activation_order, or projection_rule methods in this pass. Those methods shall be deferred until the Chebyshev-native model requires them.\par
\pard\sa160 2.4.5 DCT shall be allowed as a compact-weight basis family but shall not be advertised as supporting native polynomial products.\par
\pard\sa160 2.4.6 Chebyshev may declare supports_native_products as true for future use, but no current sheet-geometry code shall depend on that capability.\par
\pard\sa160 2.4.7 Adding a later compact-weight basis should require adding one BasisSpec implementation, one registry entry, and basis-specific tests. It shall not require editing wrappers, naming, config validation, checkpoint identity, and materialisers separately.\par
\page
\pard\b\fs30 3 Common compact-geometry requirements\b0\fs22\par
\pard\sa160 3.1.1 Every compact geometry shall define compressed axes, whole axes, coefficient shapes, consumed compact orders, and materialisation formula.\par
\pard\sa160 3.1.2 All compact geometries shall share one basis-family identity mechanism and record basis family and basis version through the basis registry.\par
\pard\sa160 3.1.3 All compact geometries shall be expressible through the unified MLP/QKV/attention-output component resolver.\par
\pard\sa160 3.1.4 Dense shall remain a conventional GPT control path and shall not require compact selector fields.\par
\pard\sa160 3.1.5 Compact execution may materialise dense-equivalent weights locally, but persistent trainable state shall be the compact coefficient representation.\par
\pard\sa160 3.1.6 No semantic sheet preset shall share a basis across QKV role or attention head.\par
\pard\sa160 3.1.7 No semantic MLP sheet preset shall share a basis across hidden_channel.\par
\pard\sa160 3.1.8 The implementation shall report enough geometry metadata that a run can be understood without reverse-engineering code or W&B names.\par
\pard\sa160 3.1.9 All new compact code paths shall preserve existing working paths unless a branch is explicitly declared checkpoint-breaking.\par
\pard\sa160 3.1.10 A compact preset name shall describe architecture, not implementation history. Historical aliases may exist, but canonical names shall be clear.\par
\pard\sa160 3.1.11 Basis-family validation shall be registry-driven. Literal chebyshev-or-dct conditionals shall not spread into wrappers, resolver code, materialisers, or checkpoint identity.\par
\page
\pard\b\fs30 4 Existing compact geometries\b0\fs22\par
\pard\sa220 The existing compact geometries remain important baselines. They are not archaeological leftovers. The new semantic sheet work should make them cleaner and more explicit, not bury them under more ad-hoc dispatch code.\par
\pard\f1\fs18\sa120 Preset\tab Canonical interpretation\tab Requirement note\par
\pard\f1\fs18\sa120 legacy_sheet_col\tab alias for generic_sheet_col\tab accepted indefinitely as input.\par
\pard\f1\fs18\sa120 generic_sheet_col\tab depth + flattened input-axis sheet\tab canonical name for current legacy sheet-column geometry.\par
\pard\f1\fs18\sa120 depth\tab depth-only compact matrices\tab matrix output and input axes remain whole.\par
\pard\f1\fs18\sa120 mlp_block\tab MLP block + depth attention\tab compresses both MLP axes.\par
\pard\f1\fs18\sa120 head_aware_block\tab depth MLP + head-aware attention\tab head-aware QKV and attention-output components.\par
\pard\f1\fs18\sa120 full_block\tab mlp_block + head-aware attention\tab existing full block composition.\par
\pard\b\fs26 4.1 Specific observations retained from prior drafts\b0\fs22\par
\pard\sa220 generic_sheet_col keeps output rows whole and compresses the input axis. For QKV, this means Q/K/V role, head, and local channel distinctions are preserved on the output-row side because those distinctions are encoded in rows. For attention output, however, the compressed input columns correspond to flattened head x local_head_channel, so generic_sheet_col does smear that semantic input structure.\par
\pard\sa220 depth is the cleanest geometric control because it changes only the layer axis. Its drawback is that it leaves every matrix element as an independent depth trajectory, so persistent parameter count can remain large. Its value is architectural interpretability and as a baseline for whether matrix-axis compression is helping or hurting.\par
\pard\sa220 BLOCK-style geometries changed semantic decomposition and bilinear field factorisation together. That made some earlier experiments hard to interpret. The semantic sheet ladder is designed to make this more decomposable.\par
\page
\pard\b\fs30 5 New semantic sheet geometries\b0\fs22\par
\pard\f1\fs18\sa120 Base option\tab Applies to\tab Compressed axes\tab Whole axes\par
\pard\f1\fs18\sa120 generic_sheet_row\tab all matrix families\tab depth, output_rows\tab input_cols\par
\pard\f1\fs18\sa120 sheet_mlp\tab MLP up/down\tab depth, d_model input/output\tab hidden_channel\par
\pard\f1\fs18\sa120 sheet_qkv\tab QKV\tab depth, d_model_input\tab qkv_role, head, local_head_channel\par
\pard\f1\fs18\sa120 sheet_out_dmodel\tab attention output\tab depth, d_model_output\tab head, local_head_channel\par
\pard\f1\fs18\sa120 sheet_out_local\tab attention output\tab depth, local_head_channel\tab d_model_output, head\par
\pard\b\fs26 5.1 Semantic MLP sheet\b0\fs22\par
\pard\sa220 The semantic MLP sheet keeps hidden_channel whole. For the expansion matrix, each hidden channel owns a depth x d_model_input sheet. For the contraction matrix, each hidden channel owns a depth x d_model_output sheet. This is deliberately different from a full MLP block, which compresses both MLP axes. This component consumes P and X. It shall not consume Y because hidden_channel is whole.\par
\pard\b\fs26 5.2 Semantic QKV sheet\b0\fs22\par
\pard\sa220 The semantic QKV sheet treats qkv_role, head, and local_head_channel as whole categorical axes. For each role, head, and local channel, it learns a depth x d_model_input sheet. This component consumes P and Q. It shall not consume J because local_head_channel is whole.\par
\pard\b\fs26 5.3 Semantic attention-output alternatives\b0\fs22\par
\pard\sa220 Attention output is the ambiguous case. There are two plausible semantic sheets and both must be available. sheet_out_dmodel keeps head and local_head_channel whole and compresses depth x d_model_output. sheet_out_local keeps d_model_output and head whole and compresses depth x local_head_channel. Neither alternative should be silently treated as the other.\par
\page
\pard\b\fs30 6 Coefficient-shape requirements\b0\fs22\par
\pard\f1\fs18\sa120 Component\tab Dense-equivalent family\tab Coefficient shape\tab Orders\par
\pard\f1\fs18\sa120 depth\tab W[out, in]\tab coeff[out, in, P]\tab P\par
\pard\f1\fs18\sa120 generic_sheet_col\tab W[out, in]\tab coeff[out, P, q_in]\tab P + q_in\par
\pard\f1\fs18\sa120 generic_sheet_row\tab W[out, in]\tab coeff[in, P, q_out]\tab P + q_out\par
\pard\f1\fs18\sa120 mlp_block up\tab W_up[M, D]\tab coeff[P, Y, X]\tab P + X + Y\par
\pard\f1\fs18\sa120 mlp_block down\tab W_down[D, M]\tab coeff[P, X, Y]\tab P + X + Y\par
\pard\f1\fs18\sa120 head_aware_block Q/K/V\tab W_role[head, local, d_model_in]\tab coeff[head, P, J, Q]\tab P + J + Q\par
\pard\f1\fs18\sa120 head_aware_block out\tab W_out[d_model_out, head, local]\tab coeff[head, P, Q, O]\tab P + Q + O\par
\pard\f1\fs18\sa120 sheet_mlp up\tab W_up[hidden, d_model_in]\tab coeff[hidden, P, X]\tab P + X\par
\pard\f1\fs18\sa120 sheet_mlp down\tab W_down[d_model_out, hidden]\tab coeff[hidden, P, X]\tab P + X\par
\pard\f1\fs18\sa120 sheet_qkv\tab W_qkv[role, head, local, d_model_in]\tab coeff[role, head, local, P, Q]\tab P + Q\par
\pard\f1\fs18\sa120 sheet_out_dmodel\tab W_out[d_model_out, head, local]\tab coeff[head, local, P, Q]\tab P + Q\par
\pard\f1\fs18\sa120 sheet_out_local\tab W_out[d_model_out, head, local]\tab coeff[d_model_out, head, P, O]\tab P + O\par
\pard\b\fs26 6.1 Materialisation formulas\b0\fs22\par
\pard\f2\fs18\sa80 depth:             W_l[o,i] = sum_p coeff[o,i,p] * B_depth[l,p]\par
\pard\f2\fs18\sa80 generic_sheet_col: W_l[o,i] = sum_pq coeff[o,p,q] * B_depth[l,p] * B_in[i,q]\par
\pard\f2\fs18\sa80 generic_sheet_row: W_l[o,i] = sum_pq coeff[i,p,q] * B_depth[l,p] * B_out[o,q]\par
\pard\f2\fs18\sa80 block:             W_l[o,i] = sum_pab coeff[p,a,b] * B_depth[l,p] * B_out[o,a] * B_in[i,b]\par
\pard\f2\fs18\sa80 sheet_qkv:         W_l[r,h,c,i] = sum_pq coeff[r,h,c,p,q] * B_depth[l,p] * B_d_model_in[i,q]\par
\pard\f2\fs18\sa80 sheet_out_dmodel:  W_l[o,h,c] = sum_pq coeff[h,c,p,q] * B_depth[l,p] * B_d_model_out[o,q]\par
\pard\f2\fs18\sa80 sheet_out_local:   W_l[o,h,c] = sum_po coeff[o,h,p,o2] * B_depth[l,p] * B_local[c,o2]\par
\pard\b\fs26 6.2 Biases, vectors, and embeddings\b0\fs22\par
\pard\sa220 This specification is about repeated matrix-family geometry. Existing vector or bias compact handling may continue, but it shall not determine the meaning of matrix geometry names. Embeddings and positional embeddings are outside this compact matrix-family contract unless a later specification explicitly brings them in.\par
\page
